default.
default&#xa0;
default4.3.2
default. 
defaultImportant
defaultly, for the PRS the Government is pursuing a policy of using Universal Credit
default to improve financial responsibility and financial ma
defaultnagement skills on the part of c
defaultlaimants.  Whilst we feel that this is a worthwhile exercise in all other parts of 
defaulta claimant’s life, a home is the one thing that needs to be stable for the individual to prosper.  Simulating a monthly salary to benefits claimant
defaults is a risky strategy when a significant number 
defaultwill have bee
defaultn used to weekly rent payments. 
default 
defaultCurrently, p
defaultayment of different benefits at different times of the month also helps these tenants to budget. 
default The long wait between payments and inexperience of money management with benefit claimants could have serious implications on bot
defaulth the landlord and the tenant
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.3.3. 
defaultIt is not fair to expect that a private landlord will 
defaultbe able to absorb the cost and risk of mounting rent arrears compared with a large social landlord as many simply do not operate on that scale or have resources as back up when things go wrong
default. 
defaultMost importantly, they do not have any public subsidy for providing housing for those tenants who would normally rent with a social landlord. 
default&#xa0;
default4.3.4. 
defaultWe appreciate that the intention is that those who cannot manage their own financial affairs or are unl
defaultikely to pay rent should be identified as being vulnerable at
default the outset and arrangements will t
defaulthen
default be
default made which can include direct payment to the landlord.  
defaultThe
default system of vulnerability should be assessed according to the tenant’s interest of keeping a ro
defaultof over their head and the landlord’s interest to receive the money, as well as the public interest of making sure that the benefit is u
defaultsed for its intended purpose. We do question how robust these mechanics currently are.
default&#xa0;
default4.4.    defaultThe greater risk of incrdefaulteasing rent adefaultrrears and homelessness overalldefault&#xa0;default4.4.1. 
defaultThe
default introduction of the Local Housing Allowance and the resulting switch to paying benefit to the tenant instead of direct to the landlord has already had profound implications and landlords have reported increasing problems with arrears.  This ca
defaultn only get w
defaultorse when Universal Credit is rolled out nationally and we would urge the government to listen to the concerns of our members. 
defaultWe remain strongly of the view that
default the tenant should be offered the choice to receive their housing cots directly or for them to
default be paid directly to the landlord.
