default6.       defaultThe longer term effects of Welfare Reforms default&#xa0;default6.1.    
defaultWe feel that the welfare changes provide an opportunity to take a wider view on housing supply and ways to ensure that landlords
default in the private rented sector remain willing to continue to provide housing to benefit claimants who are out of work 
defaultor in work but on a low income.
default&#xa0;
default6.2.    
defaultIn terms of the amount of housing costs payable we recognise that the transfer of LHA into Univers
defaultal Credit is relatively seamless with no changes being made to how the rates
default are calculated. 
defaultHowever, we are concerned that by no longer linking local housing allowance rates to market rents there
default are two key wider implications:
default 
default&#xa0;
defaulta. 
defaultThose private landlord
defaults who only rent their properties to benefit claimants because of demand for low rent housing in their areas will not feel there is any incentive to
default continue to invest if the rates
default d
defaulto not rise with market rates. 
defaultThis will then add to the already shortage of
default affordable rental accommodatio
defaultn in the private rented sector.
default&#xa0;
defaultb. 
defaultHousing conditions will be compromised if landlords are not able to increase rent in line with other market rents and in a climate where the cost of living is rising
default. This will affect the way 
defaultlandlords maintain and repair their properties if they do not have the mone
defaulty to spend on their properties.
default&#xa0;
default6.3.    
defaultWe feel that the longer term willingness of private landlords to continue to rent to benefit claimants will be co
defaultmpromised as rents move away from market
default rents. We perceive the fixed one per cent
default maximum rise in rates for 2013/14 and 2014/15 as well as the Government
default’
defaults previous policy of
default linking rises in rates to the Consumer P
defaultr
defaultices I
defaultndex to be a major threat so far as sufficient provision of accommodation to claimants is concerned.  In many areas landlords are able to 
defaultswitch to non-benefit claimants;
default this is something that we have repeatedly warned of and we can back this up by our re
defaultcent survey findings. 
default&#xa0;
default6.4.    
defaultThis must be looked at in the wider context of housing supply. This is particularly true in L
defaultondon and other hotspots.  The G
defaultovernment contend
defaults that it is, 
defaultin effect
default,
default a large purchaser who can use reductions in rates to infl
defaultue
defaultnce the market. W
defaulte question this assertion
default,
default but
default,
default even if it is correct
default,
default it will not work in those areas where the landlord is able to let to a non-benefit claimant.  A far better way is to improve supply which will then let the market restrain rents. 
default&#xa0;
default6
default.5.     
defaultA key function of housing benefit must be support those
default working on low wages. As Beverid
defaultge pointed out
default,
default it is essential that rates of housing benefit reflect local rental market conditions.  If you are on low wages and you do not get this extra sup
defaultport what is the
default point in working at all?
default&#xa0;
default7.       defaultConclusion default&#xa0;default7.1. 
default   
defaultBoth
default the welfare reforms and the introduction of Universal Credit come with considerable risks. 
defaultThere is likely to be
default be a much higher level of arrears, an unwillingness of landlords 
defaultto house benefit claimants (at a time when there is huge pressure on social housing), increased unwillingness by banks to lend for this kind of property (or increased interest rate
defaults
default to reflect the risk), much higher levels of evictions and much greater hom
defaultelessness.
default&#xa0;
default7.2.    
defaultWe recognise
default that this is an evolving system
default.
default 
defaultWhat we do ask is that the C
defaultommittee an
defaultd the G
defaultovernment do not forget the risk that
default private
default landlords will be taking once Universal Credit is rolled out
default more widely and offer a workable system which encourages these landlords to participate in this important subsector of the housing market.
default&#xa0;
default7.3.    
defaultMore widely
default,
default th
defaulte government needs to recognise the long term necessity of providing less well-off tenants w
defaultith sufficient support for their housing costs in light of increasing pressures on incomes. Supply side reforms are vita
defaultl.
